modules.description: This module implements a mergeable vector with support for concurrent modifications using operational transformation. It provides functions to manipulate vectors through insertions, deletions, updates, and merging of divergent versions using a common ancestor. The structure is suited for collaborative editing systems where conflict resolution must be handled explicitly by the user.

This module implements a mergeable string vector with operational transformation, supporting precise character-level modifications. It provides functions to insert, delete, set, and get characters, along with computing and applying patches for synchronization. It is suitable for collaborative text editing where concurrent changes must be merged consistently.

Implements a version-controlled vector with support for merging divergent states using operational transformation. It provides functions to insert, delete, set, and get elements, along with diffing and patching capabilities for synchronizing states. This structure is useful for collaborative editing systems where concurrent changes must be resolved into a consistent state.

Implements a mergeable vector with support for concurrent modifications through operational transformation. It provides atomic operations to insert, delete, set, and retrieve elements at specific positions, enabling conflict-free synchronization of vector states across distributed clients. Suitable for collaborative editing systems where multiple users modify a shared list structure in real time.

This module implements a mergeable vector using operational transformation to handle concurrent modifications and enable conflict-free synchronization across distributed instances. It supports atomic operations like insert, delete, set, and merge, with precise handling of divergent states through common ancestors and patch application. The structure allows for efficient vector manipulation at both element and character level, making it suitable for collaborative text and list editing where real-time consistency is required. Examples include synchronizing concurrent edits in a shared document or merging changes from multiple users in a distributed system.
